Flipped classroom is one approach of active learning leading to better students' learning, abilities, and academic performance. The aim of this study is to evaluate the effect of applying the flipped classroom approach to MIS course, to examine the antecedents of engagement intention after participating the flipped classroom by peers, and to guide key factors of success student presentations. The quasi-experimental retrospective pre-post design is adopted during the whole semester. Eight rounds of student presentations were conducted. Data were collected after each round. Descriptive statistics, t-test, simple linear regression, and multiple linear regression were used. The findings confirm the relationships among perceived usefulness, satisfaction, and engagement intention. There were significant differences among students' perceived usefulness and intention before and after applying the flipped activities. Audience students also suggest the proper settings for the flipped classroom by peers.